Peptide Presentation Models

Author

Alistair Bailey

Published

March 16, 2025

Summary

Here Iâve created Bayesian regression models for the NSCLC peptidomes to model peptide presentation.

The key point is that whilst I model peptide presentation and get a probability for the likelihood of each peptide being presented, what I really care about is what is causing that probability.

Thereâs a lot going on here!

But the main inference is that model infers there are opposing effects on presentation from proteins presented widely across a cohort and proteins presented more strongly by a specific donor.

This implies that neoantigen candidates should be prioritised as:

  1. Top Priority Candidates: peptides from proteins that show presentation in the specific donor BUT from proteins that donât already have many other presented peptides across donors.
  2. Second Tier: peptides from proteins with no presentation history with strong binding scores
  3. Lower Priority: peptides from proteins that already have many presented peptides across donors

Motivation

We donât really know the mechanisms of how peptides get presented.

There is evidence of protein hotspots that are more likely to be presented and researchers have focused on the nature of these hotspots in terms of cellular location, ontology, protein structure and antigen presentation. Likewise the antigen processing machinery is fundamental as this is how peptides are processed and presented. The whole system is often compressed into a single metric of MHC peptide binding affinity, but sometimes includes other features such as proteosomal cleavage.

The motivation is often to identify features of interest to which machine learning can be applied.

Machine learning is of course completely valid, but it aims to identify patterns in data and make predictions, often without easy interpretation of the relative importance of the features in terms of the underlying biology.

Here I wanted to take the Bayesian approach where we quantify the contribution of features of interest to peptide presentation. This provides a better mechanistic modelling of why peptides do or donât get presented, albeit only within our data.

To be clear, this is not a model of immunogencity, but presentation comes before immunogencity. In a natural system, a peptide that is not presented cannot be observed by the immune system and therefore cannot by definition be immunogenic.

Our estimand, the parameter we wish to learn about is peptide presentation and the effects that cause it.

But if one was trying to rank peptide candidates that might be immunogenic, quantifying oneâs uncertainty about whether a peptide would get presented is crucial.

What information do we have about a lung tumour immunopeptidome?

  1. We know who it came from
  2. We know what cancer subtype it has be characterised as by immunohistochemistry
  3. We know the HLA I and II allotypes of the donor
  4. We know the length of each peptide
  5. We know the amino acid sequence of each peptide
  6. We know the protein from which each peptide arises

Importantly, we have this data for a cohort of donors and it is prior knowledge with which to construct a Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) of causal relationships affecting peptide presentation by HLA I and II molecules (FigureÂ 1).

  • The protein here is a latent variable that we donât directly observe, but is identified from the peptide sequence. Hence protein is in blue (latent) and the peptide is in red (exposure).

  • A proteins may yield multiple peptides, hence each peptide may compete with other peptides from the same protein for binding to HLA.

  • Each donor has their own proteome, but the cohort is for a known cancer issue subtype, so we assume similarity between donor proteomes and hence both donor and cohort influence the likely existence of a protein.

  • Likewise the likelihood of any HLA allotype being present is both a donor and cohort level likelihood.

From the DAG to a model

Using the information contained in the observed LUAD and LUSC peptidomes and predicted binding affinity for each peptide to either HLA-I or HLA-II for a cohort of donors I built a model to infer:

  1. The Probability of Peptide Presentation
    • For each peptide, the model estimates the probability it will be presented
  2. HLA-Specific Effects
    • How peptide length preferences differ across HLA allotypes
    • How binding score relates to presentation probability
  3. Proteome Effects
    • How the presence of other peptides from the same protein in the same donor affects presentation
    • How the presence of other peptides from the same protein in the overall cohort affects presentation (this might seem slightly odd, but weâre essentially borrowing information from other donors to understand the propensity of each protein to be presented in general)
  4. Random Effect Variance Components
    • Donor-specific variation in overall presentation rates
    • Protein-specific variation in presentation likelihood
    • Donor-proteome variation effects

Each multilevel model can be represented mathematically as follows:

\[ \begin{align} y_i &\sim \text{Bernoulli}(\pi_i) \\ \text{logit}(\pi_i) &= \eta_i \end{align} \]

where \(y_i\) is the binary outcome variable representing peptide presentation, and \(\eta_i\) is the linear predictor:

\[ \begin{align} \eta_i &= \beta_0 + \sum_{j=1}^{J} \beta_j H_{ij} \\ &+ \beta_{B} \cdot B_i + \sum_{j=1}^{J} \beta_{B \times j} \cdot B_i \cdot H_{ij} \\ &+ \beta_{L} \cdot L_i + \sum_{j=1}^{J} \beta_{L \times j} \cdot L_i \cdot H_{ij} \\ &+ \beta_{PD} \cdot PD_i + \beta_{PC} \cdot PC_i \\ &+ u_{\text{donor}[i]} + u_{\text{donor:protein}[i]} + u_{\text{protein}[i]} \end{align} \]

Where:

  • \(\pi_i\) is the probability of peptide presentation for observation \(i\)
  • \(\beta_0\) is the global intercept - \(\beta_j\) is the fixed effect for HLA type \(j\)
  • \(B_i\) represents binding_score for observation \(i\)
  • \(L_i\) represents length_diff for observation \(i\) (difference from reference length)
  • \(PD_i\) represents protein_has_other_peptides_donor for observation \(i\)
  • \(PC_i\) represents protein_has_other_peptides_cohort for observation \(i\)
  • \(H_{ij}\) is an indicator variable for whether observation \(i\) has HLA type \(j\)
  • \(\beta_{B \times j}\) are the HLA-specific binding score effects
  • \(\beta_{L \times j}\) are the HLA-specific length difference effects

The random effects are distributed as:

\[ \begin{align} u_{\text{donor}} &\sim \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_{\text{donor}}\mathbf{I}) \\ u_{\text{donor:protein}} &\sim \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_{\text{donor:protein}}\mathbf{I}) \\ u_{\text{protein}} &\sim \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2_{\text{protein}}\mathbf{I}) \end{align} \]

where:

  • \(\sim \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0}, \sigma^2\mathbf{I})\) indicates a multivariate normal distribution with a mean of zero and variance \(\sigma^2\).
  • \(\mathbf{I}\) is the identity matrix, indicating that the random effects are independent of each other

The random effects allow for some random variation in donor peptide processing, donor proteomes and protein presentation propensity.

Results

  • Prior predictive checks: these confirm the model is sensible. Not included here.
  • Posterior predictive checks: what the model is telling us.

Average effects

These aspects are of most interest to us when thinking about whether a peptide we want to be presented i.e.Â a putative neoantigen.

  1. What is the effect of the peptide length on each HLA allotype on peptide presentation?

What ?@fig-luad-hla and FigureÂ 2 show is how some HLA allotypes are sensitive to peptide length for presentation, but most are fairly insensitive.

Average comparisons

  1. What is the effect on presentation likelihood of observing peptides other peptides from that protein for that donor?

  2. What is the effect on presentation likelihood of observing peptides other peptides from that protein across the cohort?

What TableÂ 1, FigureÂ 3 and FigureÂ 4 show is the opposing effects of a protein presenting peptides widely across the cohort or more specifically to a donor on the likelihood of a peptide being presented.

For example, the top line of the TableÂ 1 indicates that a peptide from a given protein is 56% less likely to be presented if other peptides from that protein has been observed multiple times across the LUAD HLA-I peptidomes.

Whereas if a donor has presented other peptides from a protein it is 13% more likely to present another peptide for a LUAD HLA-I donor peptidome.

And so on. The plots show how tight the distributions of uncertainty are.

This is why we would prioritise neoantigen candidates from proteins that show presentation in the specific donor BUT from proteins that donât already have many other presented peptides across donors. Along with choosing the optimal length for the HLA allotype and a strong binding prediction.

Predictions

Iâve taken the original pVACseq predictions that we tested using ELISpot (FigureÂ 5) and used the model to predict how likely each peptide is to be presented. Remember this is not predicting immunogenicity, but it shows how we might have chosen different candidates had we used this information.

Iâve plotted this in terms of ranking such that the pVACseq ranking is compared to the presentation ranking likelihood.

For example, for A119 HLA-II peptide 01-CANT1 was highly ranked with both predictions, and gave a very strong response. Whereas HLA-I peptide 12-PTPRT was highly ranked by pVACseq, but had a predicted low likelihood of presentation, and is also a very strong response (FigureÂ 6).

Obviously in an ideal world, weâd investigate, but it suggests that CANT1 may be a true neoantigen and PTPRT works in ELISpot, but may not have clinical efficacy. Or something else!
